@Article{GibbonsMurphy,
  author = 	 "Gibbons, Robert and Murphy, Kevin J",
  title = 	 "Optimal Incentive Contracts in the Presence of
		  Career Concerns: Theory and Evidence",
  journal =	 jpe,
  year =	 1992,
  volume =	 25,
  number =	 4,
  pages =	 "839-64",
  keywords =	 "efficiency wages incentive contracts",
  abstract =     "This paper studies optimal incentive contracts when
		  workers have career concerns--concerns about the
		  effects of current performance on future
		  compensation.  The authors show that the optimal
		  compensation contract optimizes total incentives:
		  the combination of the implicit incentives from
		  career concerns and the explicit incentives from the
		  compensation contract.  Thus, the explicit
		  incentives from the optimal compensation contract
		  should be strongest for workers close to retirement
		  because career concerns are weakest for these
		  workers.  The authors find empirical support for
		  this prediction in the relation between
		  chief-executive compensation and stock-market
		  performance. (from Econlit)",
  resume =	 "Important things: In 2-period model, 2nd period
		  slope is independent of first period output because
		  of (i) absence wealth effect in utility function
		  used (exponential). Only intercept depends on y_1,
		  through change in expectations of future output. 

		  Slope increases over time however (due to lessening
		  of insurance effect and relative increase in effort
		  effect. This link is provided by the zero profit
		  condition where y=w=c+b*y. 

		  Empirical link is provided by using CEO compensation
		  information to relate output of firm (COMPUSTAT)
		  with CEO compensation (Forbes). Problems (i)
		  Learning may not be important anymore, since CEO's
		  have high tenure with firm (ii) No external market
		  (no zero profit condition) since there seems to be
		  low mobility in the CEO market. [iii:mine] There is
		  no way up for a CEO, except renewing contracts. Is
		  this sufficient? In eq. and deterministic
		  environment, one would expect zero mobility: if the
		  market can observe profitability, then firm can
		  match any offer, guaranteeing the zero-profit
		  opportunity. Potential problem of firm-specific capital."
}



